      <h1 id="u79799-2">MONTRÉAL</h1>
     </div>
     <!-- /m_editable -->
     <div class="colelem shared_content" id="u160174" data-content-guid="u160174_content"><!-- simple frame --></div>
     <div class="clearfix colelem" id="pu79797-13"><!-- group -->
      <!-- m_editable region-id="editable-static-tag-U79797-BP_infinity" template="montréal.html" data-type="html" data-ice-options="disableImageResize,link,txtStyleTarget" -->
      <div class="ASM---p---body-text clearfix grpelem shared_content" id="u79797-13" data-muse-uid="U79797" data-muse-type="txt_frame" data-IBE-flags="txtStyleSrc" data-content-guid="u79797-13_content"><!-- content -->
       <p id="u79797-2">Infamously tagged as “sin city” by American politicians, during prohibition in the United States when people would flock to Montréal for its superb nightlife, this bustling city is an island metropolis and is probably Canada’s most eclectic destinations, with a strong mix of culture and heritage.</p>
       <p id="u79797-3">&nbsp;</p>
       <p id="u79797-5">Montréal is strongly bilingual when compared to other Canadian cities and English and French are both spoken here commonly. The city is a potpourri of cultures with immigrants from all parts of the world that include French, Scottish, Chinese, Indian, Haitian, Arabic, Jewish, Italian, Portuguese, Filipino, and Greek. With such a broad mixture of people and cultures, the cultural festivals, and the music and arts festivals that take place here are fantastically diverse and unique. Montréal is truly a European metropolis in North America.</p>
       <p id="u79797-6">&nbsp;</p>
       <p id="u79797-8">Montréal also has plenty to offer in terms of attractions. The 18th-century facades of Old Montréal, the breath-taking Basilique Notre-Dame, and the Stade Olympique offer different perspectives of the city. Shopping abounds down every street ranging from world-renowned designers, to local brand names and boutiques. Given its ethnic diversity, Montréal is also home to one of the most exciting food scenes where English pubs, French patisseries, Jewish delis and restaurants serving Kamouraska lamb all jostle for space. Montréal is known as the city of 100 festivals. There are always events and fests scheduled throughout the year.</p>
       <p id="u79797-9">&nbsp;</p>
       <p id="u79797-11">Set on an island in the Saint Lawrence River and named after Mt. Royal, the triple-peaked hill at its heart, Montréal’s boroughs, many of which were once independent cities, include neighbourhoods ranging from cobblestoned, French colonial Vieux-Montréal – with the Gothic Revival Notre-Dame Basilica at its centre – to bohemian Plateau. So come with us on this year’s Sagicor Convention and experience the largest city in Canada's Québec province.</p>
      </div>
